article: Apple iPhone 6S, Fully Unlocked, 64GB - Rose Gold (Refurbished)
review_body: Just going to say this first, I bought from ProElectronics Distributing which is a great, honest seller and delivered on time.First glance, it came great looking. It had a screen protector, and the screen was purely scratchless upon taking the plastic screen protector off. Looking at the back, it wasn't in the best condition. It had a small crack near the camera, which didn't affect the camera at all, it was purely cosmetic. It came in the original apple box, but it had an offbrand charger cord and no earbuds. I plugged in my new SIM card (which is AT&T) and it worked right away, and I tested a T-Mobile SIM card which worked as well, so it is at least GSM unlocked.The phone functions perfectly, it was fully unlocked when it came and I had to activate it. The 3D touch works, microphone, camera, and speakers. My only issues with it are the headphone jack which makes a slight clicking sound every couple of seconds when headphones are plugged in (which I'm pretty sure you can clean it to fix the problem), and the home button, which is a little loud.The last issue with the phone is the battery, which I expected not to be the best anyway. If you are having battery issues like me, where it seems like the battery should be lasting longer or it's losing too much battery while it's off, download the Battery Health app and see what percent it's at. Mine is at 79%, which means it has lost 21% of the power it can hold. This isn't much of a big deal, because you can get a battery and a tool kit for a replacement pretty cheap, (10 bucks on WalMart), but be prepared to replace your battery when you buy from here.Overall, it didn't surpass my expectations, it's basically what I expected. I won't be returning it for the crack, as I waited a very long time for this phone and I really can't wait two more weeks for a replacement (I'm a 14 year old so you can see why it would be important). With the battery replacement, it will be a great phone and will work fine for my needs.

article: Apple iPhone 6S, Fully Unlocked, 64GB - Rose Gold (Refurbished)
review_body: I was able to get the phone unlocked on Sprint after dealing with their terrible customer service telling me it was not possible. The trick is to get a brand new SIM card (from a retail location or shipped) and have the customer service activate the SIM and transfer your number to the new card. Sprint SIM cards are locked to both the IMEI and ICCID (IMEI must match ICCID in Sprint's system).The "refurbished" part of this is where it gets tricky. It seems like the device I received was originally a rose gold device that had it's internals swapped to a new phone. iTunes recognizes it as a rose gold and so does Sprint through the IMEI. The screen has slight ghosting, but it is hard to notice unless you are looking hard. The device was not refurbished with OEM parts (except maybe the back casing).
review_title: Activated on Sprint successfully, phone was probably hacked together

article: Apple iPhone 6S, Fully Unlocked, 64GB - Rose Gold (Refurbished)

Because it was a certified factory refurbished 6S, it certainly appeared to be brand spanking new in every way. After two months of use, I have had no problems whatsoever with it. That said, and as a long time android user, I still can't understand why Apple still hasn't decided to put the period, comma and numbers on the same page with all the lower case letters when texting. When I asked my son if that wasn't an inconvenience to him, his reply was, "Well, I've always owned Apple phones and always took it for granted that to punctuate or enter numbers, you have to go to another screen to select them." So, for all the Apple users out there, It's a great phone for the money, and if you're an android user, you've got some re-learning to do.
